Here’s a proofread and edited version of your Datawrapper tutorial with improved clarity, grammar, and structure:

Haverford College Libraries Digital Scholarship
Datawrapper Tutorial
About Datawrapper
Datawrapper is a web-based tool for creating interactive data visualizations in a variety of formats. It supports commonly used chart types such as bar, column, line, and pie charts, as well as scatter plots and choropleth maps. It is one of the most intuitive and accessible tools for beginners, offering a clean user interface and a robust library of tutorials with step-by-step instructions.

Datawrapper also includes several built-in features to enhance accessibility, such as the ability to add alt text for images and tools for selecting high-contrast, colorblind-safe palettes. It can even run color blindness tests on your visualization.

How to Use Datawrapper
1. Prepare Your Data
Before uploading data to Datawrapper, it must be cleaned and structured in a way the software can interpret. This step often takes the most time—regardless of the visualization tool.

We recommend using Excel or Google Sheets for basic data cleaning. For more advanced options, see the TriCo DS Committee’s Tidy(ish) Data tutorial.

Tips for cleaning your data:

Make a duplicate of your data file and rename it to indicate that it has been edited. Naming conventions like “raw_data,” “data_original,” and “data_edited” can help.

Remove extra rows above the header. These often appear in downloaded Excel files and will interfere with chart generation.

Unmerge cells in any double-row headers.

In Excel: Select the cells → “Home” tab → “Merge & Center” → “Unmerge Cells.”

In Google Sheets: Select the cells → “Format” → “Merge cells” → “Unmerge.”

Delete metrics like €, $, %, etc., from your data cells. You can add them back in Datawrapper during chart creation.

Rename your column headers using clear, descriptive titles. Avoid abbreviations that won’t be meaningful to outside readers.

💡 You can skip this step and experiment using one of Datawrapper’s sample datasets (e.g., Global CO₂ emissions) while you learn the tool.

2. Create an Account
Go to https://www.datawrapper.de.

Click “Sign up” and create a free account using your email or Google account.

3. Upload Your Data
You can:

Paste data directly,

Upload a .CSV or .XLSX file,

Connect to Google Sheets,

Or link to an external data source.

To follow along with this tutorial, select one of Datawrapper’s sample datasets.

4. Check and Describe Your Data
After upload, Datawrapper automatically identifies data types:

Blue = numbers

Green = dates

Black = text

Red = errors (e.g., empty cells or unrecognized formats)

Correct any issues before proceeding.

5. Visualize Your Data
Choose a chart type from the preview options (e.g., bar, line, pie).

Click “Proceed” when ready.

6. Refine Your Chart
From the Refine tab, you can:

Limit ranges,

Resize the chart,

Change colors,

Edit labels and axis formatting.

7. Annotate
In the Annotate section, add:

A title,

A description,

Alt text,

A link to your data source.

These additions improve accessibility and clarity.

8. Adjust Layout
Under Layout, you can:

Change chart dimensions,

Run color blindness simulations,

Check overall accessibility compliance.

9. Share Your Visualization
Options:

Static export: Download as a PNG file (no publishing required).

Web embed: Publish the visualization, then copy the shareable link or iframe embed code.

For WordPress and other CMS platforms, see Datawrapper’s embed guide.

General Accessibility Guidelines for Data Visualization
While there are no universal standards, the following best practices—based on resources such as Do No Harm: Centering Accessibility in Data Visualization by Schwabish, Popkin, and Feng, and Amy Cesal’s Writing Alt Text for Data Visualization—can help:

Provide descriptive HTML alt text to convey the chart’s meaning.

Add a link to the raw data alongside the visualization.

Use this alt text formula from Amy Cesal:

[chart type] of [data type] where [reason for including chart], with a [link to data source]

Example HTML syntax:

<img src="chart.png" alt="Bar chart of CO₂ emissions by country showing that China and the US are the largest contributors. Data from the World Bank.">
For longer descriptions, use:

<img src="chart.png" alt="Short alt text" longdesc="full-description.html">
